#X text 2892 501 The nmess object makes sure that only one bang goes through and all subsequent bangs are ignored. This is important because the arduino constanstly sends bangs while only 1 is needed.;
#X text 2238 143 the numbers here are the ASCII numbers of the letter duos a \, b c \, d e \, f and g \, h. The letter duos indicate whether or not a speaker has died, f 70;
#X text 51 1087 check the RefineReadings abstraction to see how we prevent random \, one-off readings from influencing the speakers' behaviour, f 40;
#X text 205 814 In the arduino code \, the fear levels for the speakers are labelled 0 to 4 \, with 0 being no fear and 4 being extreme fear.;
#X text 1454 103 because the arduino sends all of the information in a list \, the order in which they come through to PureData is very important. During testing \, we saw that the order would sometimes be different when booting the patch up. The "zlclear" message resets the order and if the order is correct (which is checked by the logic to the left of this comment) \, it stops resetting the order.;
